http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/Protests-against-Maharashtra-CM%E2%80%99s-remarks/article14006934.ece

The remarks of Devendra Fadnavis, Chief Minister of the BJP government in Maharashtra, made at the 89 All India Marathi Sahitya Sammelana held at Pimpri near Pune that Belagavi, Karwar and Nipani would be made part of the “Samyukt Maharashtra” (united Maharashtra), sparked off angry protests among various Kannada organisation in the boundary district of Belagavi.Activists of Kannada organisations condemned the remarks of Mr. Fadnavis and shouted slogans against him. They also burnt his effigy at the Rani Channamma Circle here on Tuesday. Kannada workers in Gokak had reacted similarly on Monday.The Rural Development and Panchayat Raj Minister and incharge of boundary dispute, H.K. Patil, described the statements of Mr. Fadnavis as “provocative” and “irresponsible” and an attempt to harm linguistic harmony and peace in the boundary areas between the two States. His remarks had come even before the Supreme Court delivered its verdict on Maharashtra’s original suit seeking merger of Belagavi, Nipani, Karwar and several other towns and villages of Karnataka with Maharashtra, and could amount to contempt of the apex court.Belagavi District Kannada Organisations Action Committee president Ashok Chandargi said the remarks of Mr. Fadnavis, although part of a customary reference made at every Marathi literary convention held in Maharashtra or in parts of Belagavi district, had come at a time when his own party’s Prime Minister Narendra Modi wanted to see a stronger federal relationship between various States.